Scenario #1

# for queue time

day_simulationqueue <- function() {
leavingtimes = c() # keep track of time done serving each customer (TIMESTAMP)
arrivaltimes = c() # keep track of each customer's arrival time (TIMESTAMP)
servingtimes = c() # keep track of each customer's serving time once seated (DURATION)
queuetimes = c() # keep track of each customer's time in queue (based on previous customers) (DURATION)
infrontcount = c() # keep track of how many people were in front of the customer (COUNT)

customer = 1 # customer counter

# initialize first person
arrivaltimes[customer] = rexp(1, 5) # A(n+1) - A(n) ~ Exp(5)
servingtimes[customer] = rexp(1, 6) # ~ Exp(6)
leavingtimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer] + servingtimes[customer] 
queuetimes[customer] = 0 # no customer before them
customer = customer + 1

while(1) {
  
  # check if last customer left past 12-hr mark
  if (leavingtimes[customer-1] > 12) {
    break
  }
  
  # arrivaltime = arrival time of last customer + how long until next customer (exponential)
  arrivaltimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer - 1] + rexp(1, 5)
  
  infront = 0 # keep track of how many people in front
  
  # calculate how many people in front
  for (i in 1:(customer - 1)) {
    if (leavingtimes[i] > arrivaltimes[customer]) {
      infront = infront + 1
    }
  }

  infrontcount[customer] = infront
  
  # servingtime = how long it takes to serve them (exponential)
  servingtimes[customer] = rexp(1, 6)
  
  # calculate queue time (leaving time of last customer - arrival time of current customer)
  queuetimes[customer] = max(0, leavingtimes[customer - 1] - arrivaltimes[customer])
  
  # calculate leaving time (arrival time + time to serve + time in queue)
  leavingtimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer] + servingtimes[customer] + queuetimes[customer]

  # increment customer counter
  customer = customer + 1
  
}

# return mean queue time
return(mean(queuetimes[1:(length(leavingtimes)-1)]))

}
# simulate mean queue time over 1000 days
meanqueuetime = c()

for (i in 1:1000) {
  meanqueuetime[i] = day_simulationqueue()
  
}
# plot distribution of mean queue time over 1000 days
queuegraph <- as.data.frame(meanqueuetime)

queuegraph |>
  ggplot(aes(x = meanqueuetime)) +
  geom_histogram(colour="black", fill="white", bins = 15) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Mean Queue Time in Restaurant",
       x = "Queue Time (hours)",
       y = "Number of Days (out of 1000 days)") +
  theme_minimal()

# for downtime

day_simulationdowntime <- function() {
leavingtimes = c() # keep track of time done serving each customer (TIMESTAMP)
arrivaltimes = c() # keep track of each customer's arrival time (TIMESTAMP)
servingtimes = c() # keep track of each customer's serving time once seated (DURATION)
queuetimes = c() # keep track of each customer's time in queue (based on previous customers) (DURATION)
infrontcount = c() # keep track of how many people were in front of the customer (COUNT)

customer = 1 # customer counter

# initialize first person
arrivaltimes[customer] = rexp(1, 5) # A(n+1) - A(n) ~ Exp(5)
servingtimes[customer] = rexp(1, 6) # ~ Exp(6)
leavingtimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer] + servingtimes[customer] 
queuetimes[customer] = 0 # no customer before them
customer = customer + 1

while(1) {
  
  # check if last customer left past 12-hr mark
  if (leavingtimes[customer-1] > 12) {
    break
  }
  
  # arrivaltime = arrival time of last customer + how long until next customer (exponential)
  arrivaltimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer - 1] + rexp(1, 5)
  
  infront = 0 # keep track of how many people in front
  
  # calculate how many people in front
  for (i in 1:(customer - 1)) {
    if (leavingtimes[i] > arrivaltimes[customer]) {
      infront = infront + 1
    }
  }

  infrontcount[customer] = infront
  
  # servingtime = how long it takes to serve them (exponential)
  servingtimes[customer] = rexp(1, 6)
  
  # calculate queue time (leaving time of last customer - arrival time of current customer)
  queuetimes[customer] = max(0, leavingtimes[customer - 1] - arrivaltimes[customer])
  
  # calculate leaving time (arrival time + time to serve + time in queue)
  leavingtimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer] + servingtimes[customer] + queuetimes[customer]

  # increment customer counter
  customer = customer + 1
  
}

# return downtime
totaldowntime = 0
for (i in 2:(length(infrontcount) - 1)) {
  if (infrontcount[i] == 0) {
    downtime = arrivaltimes[i] - leavingtimes[i-1]
    totaldowntime = totaldowntime + downtime
  }
}
totaldowntime = totaldowntime + (arrivaltimes[1]) # before arrival of first person
totaldowntime = totaldowntime + (12 - leavingtimes[length(infrontcount) - 1]) # after last person

return(totaldowntime)

}
# simulate mean downtime over 1000 days
meandowntime = c()

for (i in 1:1000) {
  meandowntime[i] = day_simulationdowntime()
  
}
# plot distribution of mean downtime over 1000 days
downtimegraph <- as.data.frame(meandowntime)

downtimegraph |>
  ggplot(aes(x = meandowntime)) +
  geom_histogram(colour="black", fill="white", bins = 15) +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Total Downtime in Restaurant",
       x = "Total Downtime (hours)",
       y = "Number of Days (out of 1000 days)") +
  theme_minimal()

Scenario #2

# simulating mean profits for 1 to 20 chefs

chef_simulationprofit <- function() {

profits = c()

for (i in 1:20) {
leavingtimes = c() # keep track of time done serving each customer (TIMESTAMP)
arrivaltimes = c() # keep track of each customer's arrival time (TIMESTAMP)
servingtimes = c() # keep track of each customer's serving time once seated
queuetimes = c() # keep track of each customer's time in queue (based on previous customers)

customer = 1 # customer counter
chefs = i # depends on which iteration in loop
tables = 5 # set number of tables

# initialize first person
arrivaltimes[customer] = rexp(1, 10) # A(n+1) - A(n) ~ Exp(10)
servingtimes[customer] = rexp(1, 3 * chefs) # ~ Exp(3 * chefs)
leavingtimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer] + servingtimes[customer] 
queuetimes[customer] = 0 # no customer before them
customer = customer + 1

while(1) {
  
  # check if last customer left past 12-hr mark
  if (leavingtimes[customer-1] > 12) {
    break
  }
  
  # arrivaltime = arrival time of last customer + how long until next customer (exponential)
  arrivaltimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer - 1] + rexp(1, 10)
  
  infront = 0 # keep track of how many people in front
  
  # calculate how many people in front
  for (i in 1:(customer - 1)) {
    if (leavingtimes[i] > arrivaltimes[customer]) {
      infront = infront + 1
    }
  }

  # servingtime = how long it takes to serve them (exponential)
  servingtimes[customer] = rexp(1, 3 * chefs)
  
  # calculate queue time
  if (infront < tables) { # if there is a table open -> serve immediately, no queue
    queuetimes[customer] = 0
  }
  
  else {
    queuetime = 0
    queue = c()
    for (i in 1:(customer - 1)) { # find how long until each customer leaves
      queue[i] = leavingtimes[i] - arrivaltimes[customer]
    }
    queue <- queue[queue >= 0] # remove negative values (customer already left)
    queue <- sort(queue) # sort in increasing order
    needtoleave = infront - tables + 1 # how many need to leave for 1 empty table
    queuetimes[customer] = queue[needtoleave] # minimum time needed to wait 
  }
  
  # calculate leaving time (arrival time + time to serve + time in queue)
  leavingtimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer] + servingtimes[customer] + queuetimes[customer]

  # increment customer counter
  customer = customer + 1
  
}

# calculate profit
profits <- append(profits, length(leavingtimes - 1) * 50 - (40 * chefs * 12)) # assuming each customer spends $0 and each chef makes $40/hr (same number of chefs for 12 hours)

}

return(profits)

}
# graph profits vs. number of chefs

# create an empty dataframe to store the results
results_df <- data.frame(Iteration = integer(), Index = integer(), Profits = numeric())

# simulate 1000 times
for (i in 1:1000) {
  simulation_result <- chef_simulationprofit()
  iteration_df <- data.frame(
    Iteration = i,
    Index = 1:length(simulation_result),
    Profits = simulation_result
  )
  results_df <- bind_rows(results_df, iteration_df)
}

rownames(results_df) <- NULL

# each row represents one iteration
results_df <- results_df |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = Index, values_from = Profits, values_fill = 0)

column_means <- colMeans(results_df[2:21])
profittochef <- as.data.frame(column_means)
profittochef <- cbind(nchefs = rownames(profittochef), profittochef)
rownames(profittochef) <- 1:nrow(profittochef)
profittochef$nchefs <- as.numeric(profittochef$nchefs)

profittochef |>
  ggplot(aes(x = nchefs, y = column_means)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = profittochef$nchefs) +
  labs(title = "Profit vs. Number of Chefs",
       x = "Number of Chefs",
       y = "Profit ($)") +
  theme_minimal()

# simulating mean queue times for 1 to 20 chefs

chef_simulationqueue <- function() {

waittimes = c()

for (i in 1:20) {
leavingtimes = c() # keep track of time done serving each customer (TIMESTAMP)
arrivaltimes = c() # keep track of each customer's arrival time (TIMESTAMP)
servingtimes = c() # keep track of each customer's serving time once seated
queuetimes = c() # keep track of each customer's time in queue (based on previous customers)

customer = 1 # customer counter
chefs = i # eventually loop through number of chefs
tables = 5 # set number of tables

# initialize first person
arrivaltimes[customer] = rexp(1, 10) # A(n+1) - A(n) ~ Exp(10)
servingtimes[customer] = rexp(1, 3 * chefs) # ~ Exp(3 * chefs)
leavingtimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer] + servingtimes[customer] 
queuetimes[customer] = 0 # no customer before them
customer = customer + 1

while(1) {
  
  # check if last customer left past 12-hr mark
  if (leavingtimes[customer-1] > 12) {
    break
  }
  
  # arrivaltime = arrival time of last customer + how long until next customer (exponential)
  arrivaltimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer - 1] + rexp(1, 10)
  
  infront = 0 # keep track of how many people in front
  
  # calculate how many people in front
  for (i in 1:(customer - 1)) {
    if (leavingtimes[i] > arrivaltimes[customer]) {
      infront = infront + 1
    }
  }

  # servingtime = how long it takes to serve them (exponential)
  servingtimes[customer] = rexp(1, 3 * chefs)
  
  # calculate queue time
  if (infront < tables) { # if there is a table open -> serve immediately, no queue
    queuetimes[customer] = 0
  }
  
  else {
    queuetime = 0
    queue = c()
    for (i in 1:(customer - 1)) { # find how long until each customer leaves
      queue[i] = leavingtimes[i] - arrivaltimes[customer]
    }
    queue <- queue[queue >= 0] # remove negative values (customer already left)
    queue <- sort(queue) # sort in increasing order
    needtoleave = infront - tables + 1 # how many need to leave for 1 empty table
    queuetimes[customer] = queue[needtoleave] # minimum time needed to wait 
  }
  
  # calculate leaving time (arrival time + time to serve + time in queue)
  leavingtimes[customer] = arrivaltimes[customer] + servingtimes[customer] + queuetimes[customer]

  # increment customer counter
  customer = customer + 1
  
}

# calculate queue times
waittimes <- append(waittimes, mean(queuetimes[1:(length(leavingtimes)-1)]))

}

return(waittimes)

}
# graph queue times vs. number of chefs

# create an empty dataframe to store the results
results_df <- data.frame(Iteration = integer(), Index = integer(), Waittimes = numeric())

  infront = 0 # keep track of how many people in front
